==English==
{{was wotd|2012|August|4}}
===Etymology===
Presumably onomatopoeic. Coined by Josh Sinder and Alex Sibbald of the band [http://www.myspace.com/hotrodlunaticsmusic Hot Rod Lunatics].<ref>Jack Endino, "[http://www.endino.com/archive/yarl.html Verb of the Month: 'To Yarl']", ''Backfire'', Summer 2000 issue</ref>
===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|en|/jɑɹl/}}
** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-yarl.wav|Audio (UK)}}
* {{rhymes|en|ɑː(ɹ)l|s=1}}
===Noun===
{{en-noun}}
# A [[deep]], [[guttural]] [[vocal]] [[style]] with affected [[pronunciation]], characteristic of male [[grunge]] and [[postgrunge]] [[singer]]s of the [[1990s]] and early [[2000s]].
#* {{quote-journal|en|9 January 2002|Patrick Berkery|url=http://clatl.com/atlanta/record-review/Content?oid=1235164|Creative Loafing|location=Atlanta|text=So pontificating on how ''Weathered'''s earnest morass of block-headed rage, grunge-lite mega-riffs and singer Scott Stapp's machismo '''yarl''' amounts to little more than Pearl Jam circa '91 for dummies is like shooting fish in a barrel.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|2008|Michael J. Vaughn|Outro|publisher=iUniverse|ISBN=9781440111402|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=tYak_STNXxcC&pg=PA10|page=10|text=One of my college kids informed me that the latest acoustic grinder hunk had covered it for a soundtrack — probably with that grungy '''yarl''' that everybody ripped off from Eddie Vedder.}}
#* {{seemoreCites|en}}
